I'll probably come up
with a million excuses

252
00:12:51,971 --> 00:12:53,404
for us to go have lunch.

253
00:12:53,438 --> 00:12:55,770
I mean, if you end up
with us, I mean.

254
00:12:55,808 --> 00:12:57,799
Ready?

255
00:12:57,843 --> 00:13:00,038
Do-- do you know
what you're having?

256
00:13:00,078 --> 00:13:01,943
I don't mean
to rush you,

257
00:13:01,981 --> 00:13:05,144
but I'm attending a 2:00 lecture
at the Parents' Society:

258
00:13:05,183 --> 00:13:08,380
"Super Mom, Trying to Juggle It All."
[laughs]

259
00:13:08,419 --> 00:13:10,853
I'll just have the burger.

260
00:13:10,890 --> 00:13:13,882
Thanks.

261
00:13:13,926 --> 00:13:16,486
I can't guarantee
that the meat here

262
00:13:16,529 --> 00:13:19,396
is antibiotic-free.
But the chef here is from Brittany,

263
00:13:19,430 --> 00:13:23,161
so I highly recommend the crepe
Bretagne. Deux, s'il vous plait.

264
00:13:23,201 --> 00:13:25,567
- Okay.
- Excellent choice.

265
00:13:25,604 --> 00:13:27,162
Thanks.

266
00:13:30,408 --> 00:13:31,966
You're from New Jersey.

267
00:13:32,010 --> 00:13:34,137
Unfortunately.

268
00:13:34,179 --> 00:13:37,706
Oh no, there are some very
lovely parts of that state.

269
00:13:37,750 --> 00:13:40,446
Friends of ours have a horse
farm in Upper Saddle River.

270
00:13:40,485 --> 00:13:41,884
- Really?
- Mm-hm.

271
00:13:41,921 --> 00:13:44,253
I-- I hear it's
really nice there.

272
00:13:44,289 --> 00:13:46,052
I'll have to take you
riding there one day.

273
00:13:46,090 --> 00:13:47,318
Okay.

274
00:13:47,358 --> 00:13:49,189
Tell me more.

275
00:13:49,227 --> 00:13:52,253
I want to know
all about you.

276
00:13:52,297 --> 00:13:55,460
- Uh...
- I'm from Connecticut, actually.

277
00:13:55,500 --> 00:13:57,832
I went to Smith.
And don't believe the rumors,

278
00:13:57,870 --> 00:14:00,031
we weren't all
lesbians.

279
00:14:00,071 --> 00:14:01,538
After graduation,

280
00:14:01,574 --> 00:14:05,374
I moved here and started
running the Gagosian.

281
00:14:05,410 --> 00:14:07,378
The art gallery.

282
00:14:07,412 --> 00:14:09,437
- Oh.
- It was a blast.

283
00:14:09,480 --> 00:14:11,448
But you really-- you can't
do that sort of thing

284
00:14:11,482 --> 00:14:12,813
when you're raising a child.

285
00:14:12,852 --> 00:14:15,582
The parties,
the schmoozing, the travel--

286
00:14:15,621 --> 00:14:17,452
Oh, excuse me...

287
00:14:17,488 --> 00:14:19,217
- Oh.
- Bitsy.

288
00:14:19,257 --> 00:14:20,849
- It's you.
- Bitsy.

289
00:14:20,893 --> 00:14:23,384
I've so been
meaning to call.

290
00:14:23,428 --> 00:14:25,658
Is there anything
at all I can do?

291
00:14:25,698 --> 00:14:27,529
Not unless you
know a hit man.

292
00:14:27,566 --> 00:14:29,966
That lawyer Jeanie Whitman
recommended was no help at all.

293
00:14:30,001 --> 00:14:31,593
I am so sorry.

294
00:14:31,637 --> 00:14:34,902
Turns out all our assets
are actually in Tucker's company's name.

295
00:14:34,940 --> 00:14:36,908
All I'm getting
is a million flat.

296
00:14:36,942 --> 00:14:39,240
That's appalling.

297
00:14:39,277 --> 00:14:43,805
If I'd known it would go this far,
I would have just turned a blind eye.

298
00:14:43,849 --> 00:14:47,080
Anyway, enjoy the rest
of your lunch before I ruin that too.

299
00:14:47,118 --> 00:14:49,678
I'll call you later
this week, sweetheart.

300
00:14:53,659 --> 00:14:56,628
Such a shame.

301
00:14:56,662 --> 00:14:59,893
But she should have seen it
coming-- everyone else did.

302
00:14:59,932 --> 00:15:02,560
Anyway, where were we?
Ah yes.

303
00:15:02,601 --> 00:15:05,126
After Gagosian,

304
00:15:05,169 --> 00:15:07,797
I met Mr. X.

305
00:15:10,174 --> 00:15:12,642
You know, my grandmother
worked as a domestic

306
00:15:12,678 --> 00:15:14,373
so we wouldn't have to.

307
00:15:14,412 --> 00:15:16,573
And here you are,
fresh out of college

308
00:15:16,615 --> 00:15:19,015
voluntarily taking
a nanny gig.

309
00:15:19,050 --> 00:15:21,780
I told you, this is not
a lifelong commitment.

310
00:15:21,820 --> 00:15:24,516
Okay? It's just a way
for me to get my head together.

311
00:15:24,556 --> 00:15:26,319
Besides,
the money is great.

312
00:15:26,357 --> 00:15:28,518
I finally get to
move to the city.

313
00:15:28,560 --> 00:15:31,222
I'm moving to the city
to go to grad school,

314
00:15:31,262 --> 00:15:32,889
not to be somebody's
servant.

315
00:15:32,932 --> 00:15:35,423
Plus you know you're wrong,
or you wouldn't be lying to your mother.

316
00:15:35,466 --> 00:15:37,957
This is all just
happening too fast.

317
00:15:38,002 --> 00:15:41,335
I don't understand why you can't
just live at the house for a while,

318
00:15:41,372 --> 00:15:42,669
just to get on your feet.

319
00:15:42,708 --> 00:15:44,676
Mom, I lived at home through
four years of college.

320
00:15:44,710 --> 00:15:46,075
Don't you think
that's long enough?

321
00:15:46,110 --> 00:15:47,839
Well, how could you find
a decent apartment so fast?

322
00:15:47,880 --> 00:15:51,008
The bank has, you know,
an excellent program.

323
00:15:51,049 --> 00:15:53,176
They got me hooked up with
a trainee, which is great.

324
00:15:53,217 --> 00:15:55,048
I'm getting in
the car.

325
00:15:55,086 --> 00:15:56,849
Can I come with you?

326
00:15:56,889 --> 00:15:59,619
I would feel a lot better if I could
at least see where you were living.

327
00:15:59,658 --> 00:16:01,683
Come on. The other
trainees, you know,

328
00:16:01,727 --> 00:16:04,195
they went to fancy
boarding schools

329
00:16:04,228 --> 00:16:05,786
and European exchange
programs.

330
00:16:05,831 --> 00:16:09,198
I show up with my mom,
I'll just look like a big dork.

331
00:16:09,233 --> 00:16:11,394
Guess that makes sense.

332
00:16:11,436 --> 00:16:12,926
Come here.

333
00:16:12,972 --> 00:16:14,234
I love you.

334
00:16:14,272 --> 00:16:16,638
Let me know the minute
I can visit you.

335
00:16:16,675 --> 00:16:18,540
I'll call you when
I get there, okay?

336
00:16:21,647 --> 00:16:24,582
[singing with radio]
#  Freedom, freedom... # 

337
00:16:24,650 --> 00:16:26,379
Hey, you're gonna
get me a ticket.

338
00:16:26,417 --> 00:16:28,851
# freedom #

339
00:16:28,887 --> 00:16:31,219
#  You got to give
what you take... # 

340
00:16:31,255 --> 00:16:34,315
- You're crazy.
-# freedom #

341
00:16:34,359 --> 00:16:36,987
-# freedom...#
- Sing it again.

342
00:16:37,028 --> 00:16:39,394
# freedom #

343
00:16:39,430 --> 00:16:42,558
Both:
#  You got to give what you take. # 

344
00:16:45,303 --> 00:16:47,498
Annie:
I love that song.

345
00:16:49,140 --> 00:16:51,267
Lynette:
I'm telling you, like the bees,

346
00:16:51,309 --> 00:16:53,402
you're free, girl.

347
00:16:53,444 --> 00:16:54,968
That's okay, I'll
take care of it, miss.

348
00:16:55,013 --> 00:16:56,776
Oh, thank you.

349
00:16:56,815 --> 00:16:58,680
I can't believe this.
I could get used to this.

350
00:16:58,717 --> 00:17:01,584
- I'm telling you that.
- Thank God I'm getting a shrink degree.

351
00:17:01,620 --> 00:17:04,350
You know, I love you,
but you're harsh.

352
00:17:04,389 --> 00:17:06,084
- [laughs]
- A little bit.

353
00:17:06,124 --> 00:17:08,592
Just give me a hug.

354
00:17:08,627 --> 00:17:12,393
Mwah! I'll see
you soon, I'm sure.

355
00:17:12,430 --> 00:17:13,863
Annie?

356
00:17:15,333 --> 00:17:18,427
You know the path
of least resistance?

357
00:17:18,469 --> 00:17:20,300
It can lead through
a minefield.

358
00:17:20,338 --> 00:17:22,169
[knocking]

359
00:17:28,312 --> 00:17:29,904
Oh, hi.

360
00:17:29,948 --> 00:17:32,382
You are the new nanny?

361
00:17:32,417 --> 00:17:35,113
Yes, and you must
be Maria.

362
00:17:35,153 --> 00:17:37,417
- Nice to meet you.
- Hmm.

363
00:17:37,455 --> 00:17:39,582
Can I come in?

364
00:17:39,625 --> 00:17:41,525
Okay.

365
00:17:41,560 --> 00:17:43,221
Leave it there.

366
00:17:43,261 --> 00:17:44,785
The floor is clean.

367
00:17:44,830 --> 00:17:46,821
Mmm.

368
00:17:52,170 --> 00:17:53,603
Wow.

369
00:17:53,639 --> 00:17:56,665
This place is
incredible.

370
00:17:56,708 --> 00:18:00,269
I hope you last longer
than the last one.

371
00:18:00,311 --> 00:18:02,006
Who, Bertie?
Oh yeah.

372
00:18:02,046 --> 00:18:04,014
Mrs. X told me that she
left to get married.

373
00:18:04,048 --> 00:18:06,983
Married? She had one date
and she get fired.

374
00:18:09,721 --> 00:18:13,020
Oh, Maria? Are you gonna tell
Mrs. X that I've arrived?

375
00:18:13,057 --> 00:18:15,025
Mrs. X is shopping.

376
00:18:15,059 --> 00:18:17,027
But she left you
a note on the table.

377
00:18:17,061 --> 00:18:19,621
Now I have to go run
the vacuum, okay?

378
00:18:19,665 --> 00:18:21,690
Ay...
[muttering in Spanish]

379
00:18:27,338 --> 00:18:29,704
[vacuum humming]

380
00:18:34,646 --> 00:18:36,045
Mrs. X's voice:
"Dear Nanny,

381
00:18:36,080 --> 00:18:38,048
welcome!"

382
00:18:38,082 --> 00:18:40,243
Annie's voice:
Please make note that from here on in,

383
00:18:40,284 --> 00:18:43,913
I'm referred to as "Nanny" by all
the people in the Xs' social network.

384
00:18:43,956 --> 00:18:46,823
Mrs. X's voice:
I'm so excited to have you on board.

385
00:18:46,859 --> 00:18:49,760
Please make yourself
completely at home.

386
00:18:49,795 --> 00:18:52,525
Manuel is making you
your own set of keys.

387
00:18:52,564 --> 00:18:54,532
- Annie: Mmm.
- You should have them by tomorrow.

388
00:18:54,566 --> 00:18:56,329
The fridge
is well-stocked.

389
00:18:56,367 --> 00:18:58,028
Annie:
Tofu cutlets?

390
00:18:58,069 --> 00:19:00,264
- Ugh.
- Help yourself to anything.

391
00:19:00,304 --> 00:19:01,566
Yuck.

392
00:19:01,607 --> 00:19:04,007
Sorry I could not
be there to meet you

393
00:19:04,041 --> 00:19:06,635
but I'm trying to squeeze
in a little shopping

394
00:19:06,678 --> 00:19:08,646
before my
Parents' Society meeting,

395
00:19:08,680 --> 00:19:10,511
which reminds me--

396
00:19:10,548 --> 00:19:12,982
please pick Grayer up
from the Christian preschool...

397
00:19:13,017 --> 00:19:14,746
- Wow!
- ...at 2:15 sharp.

398
00:19:14,786 --> 00:19:17,482
It's extremely important
not to be late.

399
00:19:17,522 --> 00:19:18,784
Ooh.

400
00:19:18,824 --> 00:19:20,189
As you can see,

401
00:19:20,224 --> 00:19:22,590
I have attached a list
of basic house rules.

402
00:19:22,628 --> 00:19:25,392
- Annie: Hello, Manolo.
- We believe it's important

403
00:19:25,429 --> 00:19:28,921
to maintain some sense
of structure in our home

404
00:19:28,967 --> 00:19:30,594
- for Grayer's sake.
- [thudding]

405
00:19:30,636 --> 00:19:32,228
- [gasps]
- Rule number one:

406
00:19:32,270 --> 00:19:34,966
Grayer and his playmates
are never allowed

407
00:19:35,006 --> 00:19:36,974
- in the master bedroom.
- Oops.

408
00:19:37,008 --> 00:19:40,409
Of course, you should refrain from
entering our bedroom as well.

409
00:19:40,444 --> 00:19:42,344
Rule number two:

410
00:19:42,380 --> 00:19:44,644
Grayer is never allowed
to nap during the day.

411
00:19:44,683 --> 00:19:45,945
Annie: No naps?

412
00:19:45,984 --> 00:19:48,214
This throws his sleeping
schedule completely off.

413
00:19:48,252 --> 00:19:51,187
And I prefer him tired
when I get home.

414
00:19:53,659 --> 00:19:55,524
Rule number three:

415
00:19:55,561 --> 00:19:58,029
- we just had the walls redone.
- Mm-hm.

416
00:19:58,062 --> 00:20:00,189
Please keep Grayer from
rubbing up against them.

417
00:20:00,231 --> 00:20:01,960
- Oh!
- Rule number four:

418
00:20:02,000 --> 00:20:04,696
if school is
ever canceled,

419
00:20:04,736 --> 00:20:07,762
the following nonstructured
outings are permissible--

420
00:20:07,806 --> 00:20:10,001
the Met,

421
00:20:10,041 --> 00:20:11,702
the Morgan Library,

422
00:20:11,743 --> 00:20:13,904
the French
Culinary Institute,

423
00:20:13,946 --> 00:20:15,937
the New York
Stock Exchange.

424
00:20:15,981 --> 00:20:17,642
- Rule number five:
- Annie: Rule number five!

425
00:20:17,683 --> 00:20:20,345
--we do not take
the subway because of germs.

426
00:20:20,384 --> 00:20:22,284
- Annie: Oh God.
- Rule number six:

427
00:20:22,320 --> 00:20:24,584
Grayer still must
be in a stroller

428
00:20:24,623 --> 00:20:26,784
- when crossing Park or Madison.
- Blah blah blah.

429
00:20:26,825 --> 00:20:29,385
Rule number seven:
Grayer maintains

430
00:20:29,427 --> 00:20:31,418
a high-soy
organic diet.

431
00:20:31,462 --> 00:20:32,986
Rule number eight:

432
00:20:33,030 --> 00:20:36,261
practice French with Grayer
at least three times a week.

433
00:20:36,300 --> 00:20:38,791
His father wants him to
attend Collegiate

434
00:20:38,837 --> 00:20:40,566
where he's currently
wait-listed.

435
00:20:40,606 --> 00:20:42,597
French?
Holy merde.

436
00:20:42,641 --> 00:20:44,836
His acceptance is
a top priority.

437
00:20:44,876 --> 00:20:47,037
Mon Dieu.

438
00:20:47,078 --> 00:20:49,012
- Mrs. X: Nanny?
- [Annie farts]

439
00:20:49,046 --> 00:20:51,446
[Annie moans]

440
00:20:51,482 --> 00:20:53,950
- Nanny?
- [gasps]

441
00:20:53,986 --> 00:20:55,613
- What are you doing?
- The note said

442
00:20:55,654 --> 00:20:57,986
to pick up Grayer
from school at 2:15.

443
00:20:58,022 --> 00:20:59,080
Hm.

444
00:20:59,123 --> 00:21:01,023
And it's only--
it's only 1:00.

445
00:21:01,058 --> 00:21:04,892
So I was a little sweaty from moving
and I thought that I would, you know...

446
00:21:04,930 --> 00:21:08,559
What I mean is, what are you
doing in that bathtub?

447
00:21:08,600 --> 00:21:11,626
And why are your bags

448
00:21:11,670 --> 00:21:13,831
strewn all over
the guest room?

449
00:21:13,872 --> 00:21:17,035
I thought that
was my room.

450
00:21:17,074 --> 00:21:18,166
No.

451
00:21:20,144 --> 00:21:21,736
No, Nanny.

452
00:21:23,749 --> 00:21:25,717
This is your room.

453
00:21:25,751 --> 00:21:27,719
Oh.

454
00:21:27,753 --> 00:21:30,017
Okay.

455
00:21:30,054 --> 00:21:32,522
- Yeah, this is...
- [bed squeaks]

456
00:21:32,557 --> 00:21:34,616
very sweet.

457
00:21:34,660 --> 00:21:36,287
[banging]

458
00:21:36,327 --> 00:21:38,158
Hmm.

459
00:21:40,398 --> 00:21:42,798
[siren wailing]

460
00:21:48,439 --> 00:21:51,499
I'm sorry.
Do you have the time?

461
00:21:51,542 --> 00:21:53,669
2:15.

462
00:21:53,712 --> 00:21:55,577
So they'll be getting out
anytime now?

463
00:21:55,614 --> 00:21:57,912
- 2:45.
- I'm sorry?

464
00:21:57,949 --> 00:22:01,715
They get out
every day at 2:45.

465
00:22:01,753 --> 00:22:04,085
Dumbass.

466
00:22:06,023 --> 00:22:07,615
Annie's voice:
It quickly became clear

467
00:22:07,659 --> 00:22:10,253
that Mrs. X had arranged
for me to arrive everywhere

468
00:22:10,294 --> 00:22:12,319
torturously early.

469
00:22:14,966 --> 00:22:18,094
Get ready, ladies.
Here they come.

470
00:22:18,135 --> 00:22:20,535
- [bell rings]
- [children screaming]

471
00:22:25,777 --> 00:22:27,870
Grayer?
Grayer?

472
00:22:29,781 --> 00:22:32,545
- Grayer X?
- Who is it you're looking for?

473
00:22:32,584 --> 00:22:35,382
- Grayer.
- I know that one.

474
00:22:35,419 --> 00:22:37,887
He plays with my
wee monster, Darwin.

475
00:22:37,923 --> 00:22:40,187
- Hy-ya!
- Ow!

476
00:22:40,224 --> 00:22:42,192
Oh, Grayer,
there you are.

477
00:22:42,226 --> 00:22:44,126
Hey, little man,
you remember me?

478
00:22:44,161 --> 00:22:45,924
Yes, and I hate you!

479
00:22:45,964 --> 00:22:48,797
What? Come on, we get
along great, remember?

480
00:22:48,834 --> 00:22:51,064
Like when we met
in Central Park?

481
00:22:51,102 --> 00:22:52,899
Let me get
your backpack.

482
00:22:52,938 --> 00:22:54,906
- [groans]
- Stop. Grayer, stop.

483
00:22:54,940 --> 00:22:56,931
Grayer:
Help, police! She's hurting me!

484
00:22:56,975 --> 00:22:59,205
- They usually start out that way.
- Yes.

485
00:22:59,243 --> 00:23:01,108
- Danger, danger!
- Just be patient, eh?

486
00:23:01,145 --> 00:23:03,079
- Let me put you in your stroller, okay?
- It'll get easier.

487
00:23:03,114 --> 00:23:04,877
- Hang on one second.
- I'm too big for a stroller!

488
00:23:04,916 --> 00:23:06,247
- Grayer!
- Help!

489
00:23:06,283 --> 00:23:07,716
- Grayer!
- Police.

490
00:23:07,753 --> 00:23:10,551
Grayer!
Grayer!

491
00:23:10,589 --> 00:23:12,921
Grayer!
Come here!

492
00:23:12,958 --> 00:23:15,290
- I hate you, I want Bertie!
- I know, honey.

493
00:23:15,326 --> 00:23:17,556
I know you want Bertie.
Bertie had to leave to get married

494
00:23:17,596 --> 00:23:19,393
or go on a date
or something, okay?

495
00:23:19,430 --> 00:23:21,864
But I promise, we're gonna have a lot
of fun together, honestly.

496
00:23:21,900 --> 00:23:25,996
All right? Now let me see how handsome
you look in your uniform.

497
00:23:26,036 --> 00:23:27,594
What's that?

498
00:23:28,907 --> 00:23:30,738
- Oh.
- Don't touch that!

499
00:23:30,776 --> 00:23:34,234
It belongs to my daddy!
I hate you. I want Bertie.

500
00:23:34,278 --> 00:23:35,939
Grayer.

501
00:23:35,981 --> 00:23:37,573
Annie's voice:
Already, one had to wonder--

502
00:23:37,616 --> 00:23:40,551
what kind of culture would
turn a father's business card

503
00:23:40,585 --> 00:23:42,485
into a security blanket?

504
00:23:42,520 --> 00:23:44,545
- [elevator dings]
- Annie: Here we are.

505
00:23:44,589 --> 00:23:47,854
Home sweet home.
First mission accomplished.

506
00:23:49,528 --> 00:23:52,725
Grayer, get up off the floor.
It's very dirty.

507
00:23:52,764 --> 00:23:54,026
Nuh-uh.

508
00:23:54,064 --> 00:23:56,464
I have an idea.

509
00:23:56,500 --> 00:23:58,297
Why don't we race
to the front door?

510
00:23:58,335 --> 00:24:00,269
Okay, last one there is
a rotten egg.

511
00:24:00,304 --> 00:24:02,932
I'm not stupid.
You're just gonna let me win.

512
00:24:02,974 --> 00:24:05,534
No, I am a mighty
good runner, mister.

513
00:24:05,576 --> 00:24:07,942
- Not with your pants down.
- Oh my God!

514
00:24:09,848 --> 00:24:12,612
Oh shit!
The stroller!

515
00:24:12,651 --> 00:24:15,381
[door closes, locks]

516
00:24:18,657 --> 00:24:20,784
Shit!
Grayer!

517
00:24:20,826 --> 00:24:23,294
You said a curse.
I'm telling Mommy.

518
00:24:23,327 --> 00:24:26,091
Grayer, I am not kidding.
Open this door right now.

519
00:24:27,531 --> 00:24:29,328
- Maria!
- Touch my fingers.

520
00:24:30,936 --> 00:24:33,200
- Ow!
- I am not letting go...

521
00:24:33,237 --> 00:24:34,864
- [elevator dings]
- ...until you open the door!

522
00:24:34,906 --> 00:24:36,134
Ow!

523
00:24:38,910 --> 00:24:40,172
Pardon me.

524
00:24:44,181 --> 00:24:46,172
I think this belongs
to Grayer.

525
00:24:46,217 --> 00:24:48,242
Rode the elevator to
the 12th floor.

526
00:24:48,285 --> 00:24:50,719
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

527
00:24:50,755 --> 00:24:52,723
Sorry, we're having a little
bit of a situation here.

528
00:24:57,461 --> 00:24:59,258
By the way, my name's...
[beeps]

529
00:24:59,296 --> 00:25:02,163
Annie's voice:
Since my job required a vow of chastity,

530
00:25:02,199 --> 00:25:04,667
it was essential that
I avoided all intimacies,

531
00:25:04,703 --> 00:25:06,330
especially first names.

532
00:25:06,370 --> 00:25:08,531
For the purpose of
this field diary,

533
00:25:08,572 --> 00:25:11,040
let's just call him
Harvard Hottie.

534
00:25:11,075 --> 00:25:13,100
I'm the Xs' new nanny.

535
00:25:13,143 --> 00:25:16,943
- Oh.
- Very new, as you can probably tell.

536
00:25:16,982 --> 00:25:20,782
Grayer:
I'm taking off all my clothes.

537
00:25:20,819 --> 00:25:23,720
Seems to be popular
on this floor.

538
00:25:25,089 --> 00:25:27,683
Mind if I take a crack
at him for you?

539
00:25:27,726 --> 00:25:30,661
Be my guest.

540
00:25:30,695 --> 00:25:34,062
Hey, Grayer,
it's your pal from upstairs.

541
00:25:34,098 --> 00:25:37,033
Hey, would you be a sport
and unlock the door?

542
00:25:37,067 --> 00:25:39,797
It's not nice to
lock people out.

543
00:25:39,838 --> 00:25:41,829
Please, buddy?

544
00:25:41,873 --> 00:25:44,307
[door unlocks]

545
00:25:44,341 --> 00:25:47,538
- Hey.
- Why are you here?

546
00:25:47,579 --> 00:25:51,743
Oh, I'm just helping out
my new friend.

547
00:25:51,783 --> 00:25:54,274
Annie.

548
00:25:54,318 --> 00:25:56,752
Annie.
Annie the nanny.

549
00:25:56,788 --> 00:25:58,983
She's your friend?

550
00:25:59,023 --> 00:26:02,584
Yes, she's my friend.
Isn't she your friend too?

551
00:26:02,627 --> 00:26:05,027
Not yet.

552
00:26:14,371 --> 00:26:16,202
- Thank you.
- Anytime.

553
00:26:18,042 --> 00:26:20,806
Annie's voice: Suddenly the world's
most notorious loner

554
00:26:20,845 --> 00:26:22,972
had two new men
in her life.

555
00:26:23,013 --> 00:26:27,382
Unfortunately, I knew that
the big one was off-limits.

556
00:26:27,418 --> 00:26:29,318
Based on my observations,

557
00:26:29,353 --> 00:26:32,254
guys like Harvard Hottie
only slum it when they're in college.

558
00:26:32,289 --> 00:26:34,621
So, instead of
following my heart,

559
00:26:34,659 --> 00:26:37,822
I focused on finding a way
into Grayer's.

560
00:26:41,465 --> 00:26:43,956
[pop music playing]

561
00:26:48,138 --> 00:26:51,164
Grayer, stop it.

562
00:26:51,208 --> 00:26:54,302
#  Why can't we
be friends? # 

563
00:26:54,345 --> 00:26:56,142
Annie's voice:
Befriending Grayer

564
00:26:56,180 --> 00:26:58,307
certainly wasn't easy.

565
00:26:59,884 --> 00:27:01,647
[laughing]

566
00:27:01,686 --> 00:27:03,278
La la la la la la!

567
00:27:03,320 --> 00:27:05,584
But then again, Margaret Mead
didn't run home every time

568
00:27:05,624 --> 00:27:08,457
- she contracted malaria.
- Whoa!

569
00:27:08,492 --> 00:27:10,517
Grayer:
You're in trouble!

570
00:27:10,562 --> 00:27:12,689
I thought this job
was supposed to be

571
00:27:12,731 --> 00:27:14,494
a way to get
your head together?

572
00:27:14,531 --> 00:27:17,796
Two weeks in and you already sound
depressed, dejected and paranoid.

573
00:27:17,836 --> 00:27:20,168
You forgot to mention
malnourished.

574
00:27:20,204 --> 00:27:22,968
I swear, all these people eat
is bean curd and seltzer.

575
00:27:23,007 --> 00:27:24,201
Ew.

576
00:27:24,241 --> 00:27:25,970
I mean, even the ice cream
is made out of tofu.

577
00:27:26,010 --> 00:27:28,376
So why don't you come down
and have dinner with us then?

578
00:27:28,412 --> 00:27:31,381
My new roomie's
making gumbo.

579
00:27:31,415 --> 00:27:33,883
It's not gumbo.
It's Creole bouillabaisse.

580
00:27:33,918 --> 00:27:35,852
I don't get it.

581
00:27:35,887 --> 00:27:39,084
You move to the city and overnight
your life becomes "Will 8 Grace."

582
00:27:39,123 --> 00:27:40,784
I'm here, knee-deep in--

583
00:27:40,825 --> 00:27:43,123
- [phone beeps]
- Shit. It's probably my mom.

584
00:27:43,160 --> 00:27:44,457
She's the only one
who has this number.

585
00:27:44,495 --> 00:27:45,621
Bye.

586
00:27:45,664 --> 00:27:48,565
- Hello?
- Annie?

587
00:27:48,599 --> 00:27:50,294
- Hi.
- My God.

588
00:27:50,334 --> 00:27:53,098
An entire week has gone by
and you haven't called me back.

589
00:27:53,137 --> 00:27:55,605
Mom, I told you I was gonna
be so busy with work.

590
00:27:55,640 --> 00:27:57,733
Oh come on.
You can't find five minutes

591
00:27:57,776 --> 00:27:59,300
to call
your worried mother?

592
00:27:59,343 --> 00:28:00,935
How are you, honey?

593
00:28:00,979 --> 00:28:03,004
How's the job?
How's the apartment?

594
00:28:03,047 --> 00:28:06,312
God, everything
is just perfect.

595
00:28:06,350 --> 00:28:08,978
I mean, the job
is a dream.

596
00:28:09,019 --> 00:28:11,453
A little challenging.
So rewarding though.

597
00:28:11,488 --> 00:28:14,582
And the apartment is
just incredible.

598
00:28:14,626 --> 00:28:17,754
- Yeah?
- And my roommate could not be nicer.

599
00:28:17,796 --> 00:28:19,161
Nanny, in the morning,

600
00:28:19,196 --> 00:28:21,027
I need you to stop at Tiffany's
and pick up Mr. X's watch.

601
00:28:21,065 --> 00:28:23,226
Then I need you to Xerox
the recommendation letters

602
00:28:23,267 --> 00:28:25,030
for Grayer's Collegiate
application.

603
00:28:25,069 --> 00:28:28,197
Also, I was thinking, we should
introduce French food into his diet.

604
00:28:28,238 --> 00:28:30,672
It might enhance his study
of the language. So tomorrow night,

605
00:28:30,709 --> 00:28:33,610
why don't you make him
coquilles St. Jacques for dinner, hmm?

606
00:28:33,645 --> 00:28:35,738
- Annie?
- Dry cleaning.

607
00:28:35,780 --> 00:28:38,772
Who was that,
your roommate?

608
00:28:38,817 --> 00:28:41,115
Mom, I have to go.
I have some work stuff to take care of.

609
00:28:41,151 --> 00:28:43,676
Wait a minute.
I want to make a plan to visit.

610
00:28:43,722 --> 00:28:45,781
- [phone clicks off]
- Ann--

611
00:28:49,026 --> 00:28:51,756
[man singing in
foreign language]

612
00:29:02,807 --> 00:29:05,776
Hi, ladies.

613
00:29:05,810 --> 00:29:08,802
So I took Madison to
the doctor this morning.

614
00:29:08,847 --> 00:29:10,815
She had grown three
inches in six months.

615
00:29:10,849 --> 00:29:13,249
You take her to
the doctor too?

616
00:29:13,283 --> 00:29:16,343
Darling, I do everything.
My job is a type C.

617
00:29:16,386 --> 00:29:18,650
- Mmm.
- Type C? What's type C?

618
00:29:18,690 --> 00:29:21,591
Oh Jesus.
Okay, newbie.

619
00:29:21,626 --> 00:29:23,924
Pay attention, honey.
Basically,

620
00:29:23,962 --> 00:29:26,897
there's three types of nanny gigs.
Okay, type A,

621
00:29:26,931 --> 00:29:30,731
you provide "couple time"
a few nights a week

622
00:29:30,769 --> 00:29:33,829
for women who work all day
and parent at night.

623
00:29:33,872 --> 00:29:35,999
Type B, you provide

624
00:29:36,039 --> 00:29:38,633
"sanity time,"
every afternoon, right,

625
00:29:38,676 --> 00:29:41,474
to a woman who mothers in
the mornings and the evenings.

626
00:29:41,512 --> 00:29:43,639
And type C,
the most common,

627
00:29:43,681 --> 00:29:46,411
you provide 24-7
"me time"

628
00:29:46,450 --> 00:29:49,510
to the woman who neither
works nor mothers.

629
00:29:49,553 --> 00:29:52,147
So, which one are you?

630
00:29:52,189 --> 00:29:54,089
I am type C,

631
00:29:54,124 --> 00:29:57,457
no question.
Although when I started I had no idea.

632
00:29:57,494 --> 00:30:01,294
I thought it would be
a kind of fun and easy job.

633
00:30:01,331 --> 00:30:03,891
You'd think
a college graduate

634
00:30:03,935 --> 00:30:06,563
would choose a job
a little more wisely.

635
00:30:06,603 --> 00:30:09,367
Actually, this job
kind of chose me.

636
00:30:09,406 --> 00:30:12,341
Chose you?
[clicks tongue]

637
00:30:12,376 --> 00:30:15,504
Please, child.
I left my country

638
00:30:15,546 --> 00:30:18,777
because I thought I could give my boy
and my sick mother a better life.

639
00:30:18,817 --> 00:30:22,446
I was supposed to be here
two or three years tops.

640
00:30:22,486 --> 00:30:25,046
And while I've been raising
these strangers' children,

641
00:30:25,088 --> 00:30:29,286
my own child has grown up
without a mother.

642
00:30:29,326 --> 00:30:31,419
That's how this job
chose me.

643
00:30:35,600 --> 00:30:37,727
[man singing in French]

644
00:30:41,371 --> 00:30:44,272
Half a tablespoon
of tarragon.

645
00:30:49,581 --> 00:30:51,845
That's dried.
I like fresh.

646
00:30:51,883 --> 00:30:55,375
Well, you know what?
Dried's all we got, okay, kiddo?

647
00:30:55,419 --> 00:30:58,252
I hate coquilles dry.
I want sushi.

648
00:30:58,288 --> 00:31:00,848
Well, then tell your mother
you want to learn Japanese.

649
00:31:00,892 --> 00:31:02,154
Mmm!

650
00:31:02,192 --> 00:31:04,092
Okay.

651
00:31:09,366 --> 00:31:12,028
- Ah!
- [Grayer laughs]

652
00:31:12,069 --> 00:31:16,005
I'm telling Mommy.
You're in trouble.

653
00:31:16,039 --> 00:31:18,200
Okay.

654
00:31:19,911 --> 00:31:22,880
That's it.

655
00:31:26,618 --> 00:31:29,644
No, Mommy says they're full
of high-fructose corn syrup.

656
00:31:29,687 --> 00:31:32,281
Well, what mommy doesn't know
won't hurt her, okay, Mr. Tattletale?

657
00:31:32,322 --> 00:31:34,916
Eat it.
Go on.

658
00:31:34,959 --> 00:31:36,950
Right out of the jar.

659
00:31:49,908 --> 00:31:52,240
It's okay.

660
00:31:53,811 --> 00:31:55,244
- Mmm.
- Mmm.

661
00:31:55,279 --> 00:31:57,804
- It's yummy, isn't it?
- This is fun.

662
00:31:57,849 --> 00:32:01,182
Yeah?
This is fun. This is fun.

663
00:32:01,218 --> 00:32:05,484
And this fun meal has to
be our little secret, okay?

664
00:32:05,523 --> 00:32:07,491
Okay.

665
00:32:07,524 --> 00:32:08,718
Okay.

666
00:32:11,763 --> 00:32:13,526
Hey, you know, we can do
lots of fun things.

667
00:32:13,563 --> 00:32:16,123
We just have to be friends
and we have to trust each other.

668
00:32:16,166 --> 00:32:18,327
- Okay?
- Mmm-hmm.

669
00:32:20,570 --> 00:32:23,300
Maybe you should have
a secret name too?

670
00:32:23,340 --> 00:32:25,672
- You want a secret name?
- Yeah, I want a secret name.

671
00:32:25,710 --> 00:32:27,837
Okay.

672
00:32:27,879 --> 00:32:30,609
How about Sponge Bob?

673
00:32:30,648 --> 00:32:32,275
- No, silly.
- No?

674
00:32:33,952 --> 00:32:37,752
All right, what about...
what about Grover?

675
00:32:37,789 --> 00:32:39,518
Grover,
I love Grover.

676
00:32:39,556 --> 00:32:43,083
You do?
All right. Grover it is.

677
00:32:45,529 --> 00:32:47,258
[door opens]

678
00:32:47,297 --> 00:32:49,765
Man:
Where's my little munchkin?

679
00:32:49,801 --> 00:32:51,530
- Daddy! Daddy's home.
- Huh?

680
00:32:51,568 --> 00:32:55,561
- Yay, Daddy. Daddy's home.
- I hear him, I hear him.

681
00:32:55,606 --> 00:32:57,836
- Daddy!
- Oh, there he is!

682
00:32:57,875 --> 00:32:59,809
Oh my goodness, I'm sorry.
Are you a little monster?

683
00:32:59,844 --> 00:33:01,675
Remember what happens
to little monsters?

684
00:33:01,713 --> 00:33:03,010
- Come here for a minute.
- No, Daddy!

685
00:33:03,046 --> 00:33:05,446
You remember?
What's wrong with you?

686
00:33:05,482 --> 00:33:07,074
- Daddy!
- Come here for a minute.

687
00:33:07,117 --> 00:33:09,745
You get viciously tickled.
You remember that?

688
00:33:09,787 --> 00:33:11,186
- Daddy, stop it.
- Huh? Hey.

689
00:33:11,221 --> 00:33:12,950
- You my little superstar?
- Yeah.

690
00:33:12,991 --> 00:33:15,289
Are you? Are you gonna
take over the world?

691
00:33:15,325 --> 00:33:17,418
Come on, answer me.
You gonna take over the world?

692
00:33:17,461 --> 00:33:19,452
- Yes.
- And when are you gonna do it?

693
00:33:19,496 --> 00:33:21,691
- Next year.
- Next year's not soon enough.

694
00:33:21,733 --> 00:33:24,793
Well, you must be Mr. X.
I'm the new nanny.

695
00:33:24,836 --> 00:33:27,327
Yeah. Heep him
quiet tonight, will you?

696
00:33:27,371 --> 00:33:29,032
I've got a merger
I'm working on.

697
00:33:29,072 --> 00:33:30,733
I don't get some
decent shut-eye tonight,

698
00:33:30,775 --> 00:33:32,470
somebody around here's
gonna be accountable.

699
00:33:32,509 --> 00:33:34,272
Daddy, come see
my dinosaur!

700
00:33:34,311 --> 00:33:36,836
- Daddy's got work to do, buddy.
- Please?

701
00:33:41,418 --> 00:33:44,512
Hey, Grayer, don't--
don't be sad. It's okay.

702
00:33:44,555 --> 00:33:47,649
Daddy's just tired.

703
00:33:49,092 --> 00:33:51,151
Grover.

704
00:33:53,564 --> 00:33:56,158
Hey, you want to
finish our fun meal?

705
00:33:56,199 --> 00:33:59,225
Come on!

706
00:33:59,269 --> 00:34:01,237
Yeah.

707
00:34:03,173 --> 00:34:05,437
#  Frre Jacques # 

708
00:34:05,475 --> 00:34:07,170
#  Frre Jacques # 

709
00:34:07,210 --> 00:34:10,839
#  Dormez vous,
dormez vous # 

710
00:34:10,882 --> 00:34:14,443
#  Sonnez les matines,
sonnez les matines. # 

711
00:34:14,484 --> 00:34:16,179
Nanny?

712
00:34:16,219 --> 00:34:17,550
Yeah, Grover?

713
00:34:19,824 --> 00:34:22,918
You'll never leave me
like Bertie, will you?

714
00:34:27,497 --> 00:34:30,364
- Grover, you know I...
- Promise?

715
00:34:33,838 --> 00:34:37,365
I'm not going anywhere.
You know that, right, honey?

716
00:34:40,577 --> 00:34:42,738
Right, Grove?

717
00:34:58,061 --> 00:35:00,120
#  Oh beautiful... # 

718
00:35:00,197 --> 00:35:01,926
Mrs. X's voice:
Dear Nanny,

719
00:35:01,966 --> 00:35:04,594
please remember that
today is the 4th of July family party

720
00:35:04,635 --> 00:35:06,296
at Mr. X's office.

721
00:35:06,336 --> 00:35:09,464
It probably slipped your mind
that costumes are required,

722
00:35:09,506 --> 00:35:12,703
so I took it upon myself
to have some delivered.

723
00:35:12,743 --> 00:35:15,712
- This is itchy.
- I know, sweetheart.

724
00:35:15,746 --> 00:35:18,442
Why do we have to
dress up?

725
00:35:18,482 --> 00:35:20,473
Annie's voice:
Freedom, Grove.

726
00:35:20,517 --> 00:35:23,077
It's all in the name
of freedom.

727
00:35:23,120 --> 00:35:25,145
Hey, guys.

728
00:35:25,188 --> 00:35:27,554
- Who is that?
- That's the nanny, dear.

729
00:35:27,591 --> 00:35:30,151
- You've met her.
- What happened to Louisa?

730
00:35:30,193 --> 00:35:31,592
[cell phone ringing]

731
00:35:31,629 --> 00:35:34,757
That was two nannies
ago, silly.

732
00:35:34,799 --> 00:35:38,291
- Yeah.
- Daddy, I'm George Washington.

733
00:35:38,335 --> 00:35:39,893
- Okay.
- Tickle me.

734
00:35:39,937 --> 00:35:42,030
No, I understand that,
Dan, because the bastard's selling low.

735
00:35:42,072 --> 00:35:44,040
- Please!
- Grayer, come on, buddy.

736
00:35:44,074 --> 00:35:46,065
- [laughing]
- Cut it out, sit down.

737
00:35:46,109 --> 00:35:48,543
- Yes yes, we're coming.
- No, it's just my kid.

738
00:35:48,578 --> 00:35:50,205
- We're coming.
- Right.

739
00:35:50,247 --> 00:35:52,374
- Well no, that's what I was thinking...
- You want me to call...

740
00:35:52,415 --> 00:35:54,975
- Grayer: Where's my card! Daddy!
- Your what?

741
00:35:55,018 --> 00:35:57,816
Where's my card!
Oh, I wanna go home!

742
00:35:57,855 --> 00:35:59,618
Hey, smile, Grove.
We're gonna go to a party.

743
00:35:59,657 --> 00:36:02,717
That's not my card.
Where's my card?

744
00:36:02,760 --> 00:36:04,557
Mr. X:
Would you get off that phone

745
00:36:04,594 --> 00:36:06,824
and tell the nanny to
give him his damn card?

746
00:36:06,864 --> 00:36:09,731
- Mrs. X: Nanny?
- Mr. X: Turn the car around.

747
00:36:09,767 --> 00:36:11,962
- Talk to the nanny, please.
- Nanny, go back and get the card.

748
00:36:12,002 --> 00:36:14,527
- [elevator dings]
- Hold the elevator!

749
00:36:17,642 --> 00:36:20,736
[laughs]

750
00:36:20,778 --> 00:36:22,905
I'm sorry.

751
00:36:22,947 --> 00:36:25,973
It's okay, don't be.
At least I'm fully dressed this time.

752
00:36:26,016 --> 00:36:28,075
So...

753
00:36:28,118 --> 00:36:29,745
[clears throat]

754
00:36:29,787 --> 00:36:31,448
I'm so sorry.
It's not funny.

755
00:36:31,488 --> 00:36:34,082
I don't mean to be laughing.

756
00:36:34,124 --> 00:36:36,217
You look very
patriotic.

757
00:36:36,259 --> 00:36:37,988
- Yeah.
- Let me hit your floor.

758
00:36:38,028 --> 00:36:39,495
Oh, that's okay.
I got it.

759
00:36:39,529 --> 00:36:42,430
Didn't grow up with the staff
doing everything for me,

760
00:36:42,465 --> 00:36:44,865
- so...
- Neither did I.

761
00:36:44,902 --> 00:36:46,301
[elevator dings]

762
00:36:46,336 --> 00:36:48,429
Really? You must have had
it really rough then.

763
00:36:48,471 --> 00:36:52,237
Okay, well, I'm glad
to give you a good laugh.

764
00:37:04,822 --> 00:37:07,882
Woman: My husband and I are
taking our second honeymoon

765
00:37:07,925 --> 00:37:09,984
in Provence.

766
00:37:11,796 --> 00:37:13,923
#  When I dance they
call me Macarena # 

767
00:37:13,965 --> 00:37:16,365
#  And the boys,
they say that I'm buena # 

768
00:37:16,399 --> 00:37:18,731
#  They all want me,
they can't have me # 

769
00:37:18,769 --> 00:37:21,294
#  So they all come
and dance beside me # 

770
00:37:21,338 --> 00:37:23,465
#  Move with me,
jam with me... # 

771
00:37:25,342 --> 00:37:27,708
I'm looking for Mr. X.
Have you seen him?

772
00:37:27,745 --> 00:37:29,770
No, sorry.

773
00:37:29,814 --> 00:37:31,805
Wouldn't know him if I did.

774
00:37:31,849 --> 00:37:34,181
#  Macarena,
hey, Macarena... # 

775
00:37:34,217 --> 00:37:37,243
Grove, come on. What is wrong?
Why won't you shake your booty?

776
00:37:37,287 --> 00:37:39,278
'Cause I have to
make a doodie.

777
00:37:39,322 --> 00:37:41,347
Oh.
Come on.

778
00:37:43,260 --> 00:37:45,820
[child crying]

779
00:37:51,534 --> 00:37:53,866
Hey, Grover, I think
the bathroom's the other way.

780
00:37:53,904 --> 00:37:56,338
- My daddy has one in his office.
- Yeah?

781
00:37:56,373 --> 00:37:58,807
- I wanna go to my daddy's bathroom.
- Okay.

782
00:37:58,843 --> 00:38:01,573
[woman giggling]

783
00:38:04,180 --> 00:38:05,579
[gasps]

784
00:38:05,616 --> 00:38:08,483
- Oh.
- Why is Daddy tickling that lady?

785
00:38:08,518 --> 00:38:10,315
I'm sorry.

786
00:38:10,353 --> 00:38:12,514
Grayer just had to use
the bathroom.

787
00:38:14,457 --> 00:38:16,925
So use it already.

788
00:38:18,829 --> 00:38:21,627
Hello, Grayer.
Remember me?

789
00:38:21,666 --> 00:38:23,634
I work with your daddy
in the Chicago office.

790
00:38:23,668 --> 00:38:26,501
Let go.
I have to make a doodie.

791
00:38:26,536 --> 00:38:27,867
Oh.

792
00:38:27,905 --> 00:38:30,840
[laughs]

793
00:38:32,643 --> 00:38:35,976
So, you must
be the nanny.

794
00:38:36,012 --> 00:38:39,413
Uh, yes, I...

795
00:38:39,449 --> 00:38:43,385
I'll get out of your--
I'll wait in the hall.

796
00:38:46,891 --> 00:38:48,518
So sorry.

797
00:38:55,733 --> 00:38:57,792
Grayer, hurry up.
Your mom's coming.

798
00:38:57,835 --> 00:39:01,066
Sweetie, did Grayer hear
from the waiting-list committee yet?

799
00:39:01,104 --> 00:39:02,867
No, why?

800
00:39:02,907 --> 00:39:04,772
Oh, I'm sure it
doesn't mean anything,

801
00:39:04,809 --> 00:39:06,538
but the Bairds did
and Darwin got in.

802
00:39:10,981 --> 00:39:14,417
Please don't say anything about
Collegiate or Darwin to my husband.

803
00:39:14,451 --> 00:39:16,442
Sure.

804
00:39:19,857 --> 00:39:22,325
- Oh, hi, pumpkin.
- There you are.

805
00:39:22,359 --> 00:39:24,759
Oh, you've met before
in Chicago, right?

806
00:39:24,795 --> 00:39:26,228
- Yes, hello.
- Lovely to see you.

807
00:39:26,262 --> 00:39:28,355
- Nice to see you as well.
- Excuse me. Thanks again.

808
00:39:28,398 --> 00:39:30,093
- Mm-hm.
- Where have you been?

809
00:39:30,133 --> 00:39:31,896
Making calls.
Where's the chow?

810
00:39:31,936 --> 00:39:33,870
- The entire time?
- Yeah.

811
00:39:36,072 --> 00:39:38,870
[thunder rumbling]

812
00:39:38,909 --> 00:39:42,310
Annie's voice:
Male monogamy remains an elusive,

813
00:39:42,345 --> 00:39:44,575
yet much
mythologized practice

814
00:39:44,614 --> 00:39:46,241
throughout the world.

815
00:39:46,282 --> 00:39:48,750
In many Bedouin tribes,

816
00:39:48,786 --> 00:39:52,483
powerful men are encouraged
to take multiple wives.

817
00:39:53,724 --> 00:39:55,624
In contemporary France,

818
00:39:55,659 --> 00:39:57,593
mistresses are de rigueur

819
00:39:57,628 --> 00:40:00,119
and quietly tolerated.

820
00:40:00,163 --> 00:40:02,791
But for the women
of the Upper East Side,

821
00:40:02,833 --> 00:40:06,860
adultery is
pathologically ignored.

822
00:40:08,571 --> 00:40:11,540
Nobody warned me we were going
to have a therapy session.

823
00:40:11,608 --> 00:40:14,475
Mrs. X: It's just that I didn't
see you at all at the party.

824
00:40:14,511 --> 00:40:17,480
Well, I was trying to
sneak in a little work.

825
00:40:17,514 --> 00:40:20,210
Okay? Forgive me
for making a living.

826
00:40:20,250 --> 00:40:23,845
But everybody else
was participating.

827
00:40:23,888 --> 00:40:28,291
Everybody else doesn't pull
down what I do every year.

828
00:40:28,324 --> 00:40:31,191
I had my family there
and I was present and accounted for.

829
00:40:31,227 --> 00:40:34,219
So now, you know, I would really
appreciate a moment of peace and quiet.

830
00:40:34,264 --> 00:40:35,788
'Cause frankly,
I'm exhausted.

831
00:40:35,833 --> 00:40:38,097
[thunder crashes]

832
00:40:38,134 --> 00:40:40,329
Annie:
Bonjour, Pierre.

833
00:40:40,370 --> 00:40:42,429
Bonjour.

834
00:40:42,472 --> 00:40:45,771
- Comment allez-vous?
- [Mr. and Mrs. X arguing]

835
00:40:48,879 --> 00:40:50,176
Bien, merci.

836
00:40:50,213 --> 00:40:52,010
Et vous?

837
00:40:52,048 --> 00:40:55,609
Ah, comme ci comme ca.

838
00:40:59,222 --> 00:41:01,281
Okay, I got
a great idea.

839
00:41:01,324 --> 00:41:05,260
Let's pretend that
we're in a cave.

840
00:41:05,295 --> 00:41:07,695
You know what, Nanny?

841
00:41:07,731 --> 00:41:09,358
What, Grove?

842
00:41:09,399 --> 00:41:11,833
I love you best.

843
00:41:13,904 --> 00:41:16,873
Annie's voice: The other nannies
had warned me about this very moment,

844
00:41:16,907 --> 00:41:18,898
the moment when you'll
be tempted to break

845
00:41:18,943 --> 00:41:20,911
the cardinal rule
of nannydom.

846
00:41:20,945 --> 00:41:25,848
And yet, staring into those big,
sad, searching eyes,

847
00:41:25,883 --> 00:41:28,875
I simply couldn't resist.

848
00:41:28,919 --> 00:41:31,285
I love you too, Grove.

849
00:41:33,323 --> 00:41:37,726
Three little words made leaving
this job 1,000 times harder.

850
00:41:37,761 --> 00:41:39,524
Mrs. X:
...hear a thing I have to say!

851
00:41:39,562 --> 00:41:42,190
I know that you work hard.
I just think

852
00:41:42,232 --> 00:41:46,635
that if-- if we're
gonna have more children--

853
00:41:46,670 --> 00:41:49,730
Well, maybe you should
focus on the one you already have.

854
00:41:49,773 --> 00:41:52,867
'Cause you can barely
handle him as it is.

855
00:41:54,377 --> 00:41:56,402
Why are you
so cruel to me?

856
00:41:56,446 --> 00:41:58,243
- Why?
- Why are you so cruel?

857
00:41:58,281 --> 00:42:00,943
Because I cannot take
the additional pressure.

858
00:42:00,985 --> 00:42:04,318
You know something? I think that
I am going to go out to Chicago

859
00:42:04,354 --> 00:42:06,822
- until this merger is finished.
- Will you stop it, please?

860
00:42:06,857 --> 00:42:09,690
And I certainly hope that
you're in a better mood...

861
00:42:09,727 --> 00:42:13,026
- Please, stop it.
- ...when I come back. All right?

862
00:42:13,062 --> 00:42:15,223
If I come back!

863
00:42:23,774 --> 00:42:25,674
[door slams]

864
00:42:28,779 --> 00:42:32,840
Nanny, this is yours,
is it not?

865
00:42:38,054 --> 00:42:41,114
Uh... no, I--

866
00:42:41,157 --> 00:42:42,954
no, I don't know
what that is.

867
00:42:42,993 --> 00:42:46,053
It was in our laundry.

868
00:42:46,095 --> 00:42:49,189
It is not mine,
it is not Mr. X's,

869
00:42:49,232 --> 00:42:51,894
so it has to be yours,
right?

870
00:42:53,403 --> 00:42:56,031
Right?

871
00:42:56,072 --> 00:42:58,063
Yes, it's mine.

872
00:43:00,109 --> 00:43:03,237
Please don't leave your personal items
lying around the house again.

873
00:43:05,014 --> 00:43:06,948
I-- I won't.

874
00:43:06,984 --> 00:43:09,646
- I promise. I'm sorry.
- Apology accepted.

875
00:43:19,429 --> 00:43:21,920
I don't mean...

876
00:43:21,966 --> 00:43:24,833
to be a control freak.

877
00:43:28,538 --> 00:43:33,407
It's-- it's just that when Mr. X
is in the middle of a big deal,

878
00:43:33,443 --> 00:43:35,707
it can be very hard on me.

879
00:43:38,582 --> 00:43:40,743
I understand.

880
00:43:40,784 --> 00:43:43,617
[thunder rumbles]

881
00:43:52,696 --> 00:43:55,631
How is Grayer doing?

882
00:43:55,666 --> 00:43:57,827
Grayer?

883
00:43:57,868 --> 00:44:00,701
He's-- he's fine.

884
00:44:00,738 --> 00:44:03,263
He's great.

885
00:44:03,306 --> 00:44:05,171
That's good to hear.

886
00:44:05,208 --> 00:44:08,769
He really is
a wonderful child, isn't he?

887
00:44:12,850 --> 00:44:15,250
He's the best.

888
00:44:15,284 --> 00:44:18,219
He's--
he's such a sweet--

889
00:44:18,254 --> 00:44:20,381
Okay, good night then.

890
00:44:20,423 --> 00:44:22,414
[door closes]

891
00:44:26,529 --> 00:44:28,656
Mrs. X's voice:
Dear Nanny, I know it's Sunday

892
00:44:28,699 --> 00:44:30,223
and you requested
a day off,

893
00:44:30,266 --> 00:44:32,325
but I desperately need
to sleep in.

894
00:44:32,368 --> 00:44:34,598
I have a very long
afternoon today

895
00:44:34,638 --> 00:44:36,731
tasting caterers
for our benefit,

896
00:44:36,774 --> 00:44:39,436
"Conga for the Congo."
Please don't wake me

897
00:44:39,475 --> 00:44:41,875
unless Mr. X calls
from Chicago.

898
00:44:41,912 --> 00:44:43,504
And most importantly,

899
00:44:43,546 --> 00:44:46,014
find a way to
keep the boy quiet.

900
00:44:46,049 --> 00:44:48,176
Why don't they just
muzzle the kid already?

901
00:44:48,217 --> 00:44:49,684
What's a muzzle?

902
00:44:49,720 --> 00:44:53,417
Scrambled for you
and Cheerios for the boy.

903
00:44:53,456 --> 00:44:55,754
Mommy doesn't allow me
to eat sugar cereal.

904
00:44:55,793 --> 00:44:57,761
Cheerios are sugar-free.

905
00:44:57,795 --> 00:45:00,457
Low in sugar isn't
the same as sugar-free.

906
00:45:00,496 --> 00:45:02,054
Grover, just eat it.

907
00:45:05,368 --> 00:45:06,926
Is that caffeinated?

908
00:45:06,970 --> 00:45:08,995
Mommy doesn't
use caffeine.

909
00:45:09,038 --> 00:45:11,336
That's because Mommy
sleeps till noon.

910
00:45:11,374 --> 00:45:13,672
Mrs. X's voice:
Perhaps it might be a nice morning

911
00:45:13,711 --> 00:45:15,906
to do something
educational with Grayer,

912
00:45:15,946 --> 00:45:17,971
like the Pissarro show
at the Guggenheim.

913
00:45:18,014 --> 00:45:20,847
Mommy said you're supposed to take
me to her favorite museum,

914
00:45:20,884 --> 00:45:22,249
the "Guggyheiny."

915
00:45:22,285 --> 00:45:24,014
Well, since today was
supposed to be my day off,

916
00:45:24,053 --> 00:45:26,613
we're gonna go to my favorite,
the Museum of Natural History.

917
00:45:26,656 --> 00:45:28,920
- Isn't that on the West Side?
- Yeah, so?

918
00:45:28,959 --> 00:45:31,951
I'm not allowed to go on the West Side.
That's a rule.

919
00:45:31,995 --> 00:45:35,692
Well, today just happens to
be break-the-rules day.

920
00:45:35,733 --> 00:45:37,894
Oh.

921
00:45:45,108 --> 00:45:47,474
Hi.
Two please.

922
00:46:18,374 --> 00:46:20,774
Hey, you know what
the biggest word in America is?

923
00:46:20,811 --> 00:46:21,937
What?

924
00:46:21,979 --> 00:46:25,142
Anti--
antidisestablishmentarianism.

925
00:46:25,181 --> 00:46:27,342
Hey, that's pretty good,
Grove.

926
00:46:27,383 --> 00:46:29,248
Actually, I know
a longer word.

927
00:46:29,285 --> 00:46:31,753
- There is no longer word.
- Yes, there is.

928
00:46:31,789 --> 00:46:34,280
Supercalifragilistic-
expialidocious.

929
00:46:34,323 --> 00:46:36,518
Wow.
What does that mean?

930
00:46:36,559 --> 00:46:39,585
Come on inside.
Let me show you.

931
00:46:39,630 --> 00:46:42,861
Annie: "The apatosaurus, formerly
known as the brontosaurus,

932
00:46:42,900 --> 00:46:45,164
is from a family of
enormous herbivores."

933
00:46:45,201 --> 00:46:47,601
Herbivores means
vegetarian.

934
00:46:47,638 --> 00:46:49,435
Like Mommy,
you know?

935
00:46:49,472 --> 00:46:51,497
What's that over there?

936
00:46:54,343 --> 00:46:56,868
That is the T-rex.

937
00:46:56,914 --> 00:46:59,508
- Is that one like Mommy too?
- Hmm.

938
00:46:59,549 --> 00:47:02,347
I wish my ancestors
made totem poles.

939
00:47:02,385 --> 00:47:04,285
Well, they did.
That one looks just like you.

940
00:47:04,320 --> 00:47:05,480
[laughs]
It does.

941
00:47:05,521 --> 00:47:06,818
Well, that guy has
a big...

942
00:47:06,857 --> 00:47:09,052
It's hanging.

943
00:47:13,362 --> 00:47:15,330
Cool.
What are they?

944
00:47:15,364 --> 00:47:16,956
They're a Matis
family.

945
00:47:17,000 --> 00:47:18,968
They live in
the Amazon.

946
00:47:19,001 --> 00:47:21,367
Which one's the nanny?

947
00:47:21,404 --> 00:47:25,465
She has the day off. Things are
different in that part of the world.

948
00:47:27,176 --> 00:47:29,406
Mrs. X's voice:
And Nanny, one last thing

949
00:47:29,445 --> 00:47:32,107
before you take
the rest of the day off:

950
00:47:32,148 --> 00:47:35,311
Do you think you could
manage a quick shop for me?

951
00:47:39,555 --> 00:47:41,523
- I'll help.
- No, it's okay, Grayer.

952
00:47:41,557 --> 00:47:43,991
Don't.
Grayer, don't-- don't!

953
00:47:44,026 --> 00:47:45,721
God!

954
00:47:45,762 --> 00:47:47,753
Mommy!

955
00:47:47,798 --> 00:47:50,358
What a mess.

956
00:47:50,399 --> 00:47:53,129
Really, Nanny, I don't know
why you didn't leave all this

957
00:47:53,169 --> 00:47:55,262
downstairs with Manuel
to store.

958
00:47:55,304 --> 00:47:58,273
I mean, am I supposed to have this lying
around the apartment till the benefit?

959
00:47:58,307 --> 00:48:01,435
No no no, of course not. I-- I'm gonna
bring it down to him right now.

960
00:48:01,477 --> 00:48:04,105
There's no time now.

961
00:48:04,146 --> 00:48:06,671
I need you to get ready for the Nanny
Conflict Resolution Seminar

962
00:48:06,717 --> 00:48:08,514
at the Parents' Society.

963
00:48:08,551 --> 00:48:11,281
I totally forgot
it was this evening.

964
00:48:11,320 --> 00:48:13,550
Um...

965
00:48:15,091 --> 00:48:16,956
[objects thud]

966
00:48:19,161 --> 00:48:21,629
Mrs. X, I...

967
00:48:21,665 --> 00:48:23,826
don't know
if you remember,

968
00:48:23,867 --> 00:48:26,028
but I-- I was supposed
to have the evening off.

969
00:48:26,068 --> 00:48:28,468
And I made plans.

970
00:48:32,074 --> 00:48:34,133
The entire point of
the seminar

971
00:48:34,176 --> 00:48:36,201
is that everybody
brings their nanny.

972
00:48:37,614 --> 00:48:40,082
Are you suggesting
I attend it alone?

973
00:48:40,116 --> 00:48:42,550
Huh-uh. No.

974
00:48:42,585 --> 00:48:44,712
I was just...

975
00:48:44,755 --> 00:48:46,416
I was confused.

976
00:48:46,455 --> 00:48:50,152
So, I will
cancel my plans.

977
00:48:50,192 --> 00:48:52,592
I'd appreciate it.

978
00:48:57,133 --> 00:49:00,728
Woman: Does anyone have
an extra diaper I can use?

979
00:49:00,771 --> 00:49:03,501
Stop eating them boogers!

980
00:49:03,539 --> 00:49:06,940
Grayer, no nudity.
Please.

981
00:49:06,977 --> 00:49:09,104
Of course you feel anxiety

982
00:49:09,145 --> 00:49:11,773
when leaving
your kids with strangers.

983
00:49:11,815 --> 00:49:14,079
You're moms.
Okay...

984
00:49:14,116 --> 00:49:16,584
now what I would
love to do

985
00:49:16,620 --> 00:49:18,815
is bring in
the nannies.

986
00:49:18,855 --> 00:49:21,346
Linda, Gillian, would you
mind monitoring the children

987
00:49:21,390 --> 00:49:23,415
so that the nannies can
